<section id="css">
  <h1>Cascading Style Sheets (CSS)</h1>
  <p>
    A language for describing the look and feel of documents written in a markup language.
  </p>

  Here is an example of CSS code: <br />
  <pre>
    p {
       font-size: 20px;
    }
  </pre>

  <p>
    This defines the font size for all <b>paragraph</b> tags.
  </p>

  <h3>CSS attributes</h3>
  <p>
    HTML tags can have many of their attributes styled.
    Examples:
    <dl class="dl-horizontal">
      <dt>font-size</dt>
      <dd>Change the size of the font for this element and all it's children</dd>

      <dt>width</dt>
      <dd>If the element allows it, set the width.  Supports different units.  Such as: 'px' or '%'</dd>

      <dt>height</dt>
      <dd>If the element allows it, set the height.  Supports different units.  Such as: 'px' or '%'</dd>

      <dt>background-color</dt>
      <dd>Change the background color.  HEX code or RGB</dd>

      <dt>color</dt>
      <dd>Font color for this element and it's children.  HEX or RGB</dd>

      <dt>Position</dt>
      <dd>How the element is displayed.  Certain position types allow the element to be moved using x,y coordinates.</dd>

      <dt>padding</dt>
      <dd>The spacing from the edges inside a container.</dd>

      <dt>margin</dt>
      <dd>The space between containers</dd>
    </dl>
  </p>

  <h3>Syntactically Awesome Stylesheets</h3>

  <p>
    Sass is a stylesheet sugar language.
    It is processed by a program and vanilla CSS is created.  It's purpose is to simplify the ugly parts of CSS as well as
    add extra functionality such reusable code.  (variables and functions)
  </p>

  <%= render "css_demo" %>
</section>